The green hit atop the tongue is matched underfoot by the midsole, which is complemented by a metallic gold shank plate as a nod to a bracelet May's grandmother gave her—May's first piece of jewelry.

The Wmns Air Jordan 14 Retro Low 'Red Lipstick' emerges in a familiar two-tone look inspired by lipstick. The Ferrari-inspired silhouette emerges with a black nubuck construction on the upper, highlighted by Gym Red along the collar, tongue and throat. A tonal quarter panel badge complements the design, while underfoot, the speckled phlyon midsole houses Zoom Air for cushioning, with a silver shank plate for stability. The sockliner sports text in a style that mimicks lipstick, with lipstick-stained tissue paper wrapping the shoe to complete the thematic look.

The CLOT x Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Terracotta' released as part of a collaboration with Edison Chen's streetwear brand. A follow-up to a 2018 Air Jordan 13 Low, the shoe features a tan suede construction on the upper, highlighted by embossed detailing modeled after protective armor—drawn from the Terracotta Army. The tongues include mismatched co-branding, while the heel includes a red Chinese knot worked through a coin that sports a Chinese idiom for prosperity and happiness.

Supreme and Jordan Brand teamed up again to create the Supreme x Air Jordan 14 Retro SP 'White.' The shoe's upper is built with white leather, accented by metal studs throughout the construction. A co-branded badge stands out on the ankle, with further co-branding on the heel. Finished in a familiar mix of white, black and University Red, the shoe is supported underfoot by a shank plate and Zoom Air, with the rubber outsole sporting a herringbone pattern for traction.

A classic Jordan Brand colorway, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Gym Red' features a familiar mix of Chicago Bulls colors. The last shoe that Michael Jordan wore on the court, the upper is built with suede, finished in Gym Red and overlaid by black on the toe. Underfoot, the contrasting white midsole houses Zoom Air and a shank plate for cushioning and stability, giving way to a herringbone outsole.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Reverse Ferrari' brings a sports car-inspired look to the sports car-inspired silhouette. The shoe's leather upper takes on Ferrari's signature mix of red and yellow, but its features the yellow more predemoninantly. University Red hits accent the tongue and heel branding, while the usual Jumpman badge remains intact. Underfoot, a tire-inspired midsole includes Zoom Air units for cushioning, giving way to a herringbone traction pattern on the outsole.

An April 2019 release, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Candy Cane' 2019 is the second retro of the festive colorway. The shoe's leather upper includes tumbled and smooth finishes as well as perforations for breathability, while Varsity Red accents emerge on the tongue, heel and midsole. Zoom Air provides cushioning, with a shank plate for stability, giving way to an outsole with a herringbone traction pattern.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro GS 'Gym Red' is a grade-school shoe with a familiar Jordan Brand colorway. Built with nubuck, the upper appears in Gym Red, contrasted by black suede on the forefoot. The signature Jumpman badge stands out on the side wall, while underfoot, the contrasting white midsole houses two Zoom Air units for cushioning, with a herringbone outsole for traction.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro ‘Ferrari’ amplifies the silhouette’s vehicular inspiration with a luxurious suede upper in a rich Challenge Red hue. Carbon fiber detailing and a yellow Jumpman badge play up the shoe’s likeness to Michael Jordan’s Ferrari 550 Maranello. The low-top kicks are finished with a chrome shank plate and additional pops of yellow atop the tongue and heel panel.

Emerging with OG-inspired color blocking, the Air Jordan 14 Retro GS 'Hyper Royal' is a grade-school shoe. Rather than Varsity Red, however, the shoe sports Hyper Royal hits throughout its construction. The upper's leather base otherwise appears in white, with perforations throughout for breathability. Underfoot, a carbon-fiber shank plate in the foam midsole is included for stability, while Zoom Air provides cushioning.

Originally releasing after Michael Jordan's second retirement, the Air Jordan 14 Retro Low 'Laney' dropped in 2015. The shoe's Varsity Royal nubuck upper is accented by Varsity Maize on the tongue, heel and Jumpman, giving the nod to Michael Jordan's high school team. The shoe forgoes the usual side wall perforations.

From 1998-1999, Jordan released eight Air Jordan 14 colorways. The Air Jordan 14 'Indiglo' features a leather and durabuck structure with white and green accents throughout. It wouldn't be until 2016 that the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Indiglo' would receive a retro.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Candy Cane' 2012 released in March 2012, bringing back a colorway that debuted in 1999. The shoe's perforated white leather upper is accented by hits of Varsity Red on the forefoot, heel and midsole, a combination that gives the shoe its name. Complemented by hits of black, the shoe is supported by dual Zoom units and vents on the outsole.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro TD 'Gym Red' is a toddlers' iteration of the shoe. The shoe's nubuck upper appears in Gym Red, with black synthetic suede contrasting the forefoot overlay. Underfoot, the white midsole provides cushioning and contrast, working with a TPU midfoot shank for stability. The outsole incorporates a herringbone pattern for traction.

With sleek style, the Nike Air Jordan 14 Retro SE 'Black Ferrari' is a streamlined revamp of the profile's initial Italian sportscar inspiration. Introduced in December 2019, the offering portrays a divergent design with ventilated leather on the lateral side and padded grey suede on the medial. AThe heelstay features a Jumpman badge and an etched '23' logo. Carbon fiber elements dress the Air-infused midsole, and red chrome divides the patterned rubber outsole.

Taking on a popular Air Jordan 1 colorway, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Black Toe' 2014 originally debuted in 1998. Like its inspiration, this sports car-inspired design features a black overlay at the toe, but unlike the Jordan 1, the majority of the upper appears in white. Varsity Red touches are limited to the branding and the heel, while the silhouette’s signature Jumpman badge stands out near the ankle.

Unveiled in December 2019, the Air Jordan 14 Retro from Nike's 'Doernbecher Freestyle' collection was designed by a patient at the hospital, Ethan Ellis. Personal elements on the shoe include a nod to his beloved TCU Horned Frogs in black nubuck with metallic blue layers and a two-toned color palette on the laces and tongue tabs. The number '6' on the right shoe heel stands for his heart surgeries, and a depiction of the Space Needle emerges on the left. The translucent rubber outsole features heart rhythm patterns.

After having no releases the year before, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Thunder' was one of four Air Jordan colorways to drop in 2014. Inspired by the design of the Air Jordan 4 'Thunder,' the black suede upper sports Vibrant Yellow accents on the heel and Jumpman badge, with the color also making its way to the midsole.

The release of the Air Jordan 14 Retro ' Oxidized ' in July 2016 marked its first retro. Legend Blue accentuates the white leather top of the shoe on the Jumpman branding and '23' on the bottom. In the meantime, Oxidized Green hits break up the black mid-and outsole, most particularly on the midfoot plate.

The Air Jordan 14's Ferrari-inspired design receives a Wolf Grey-based colorway, with most of the design's subdued yet sharp color. Sport Blue hits appear on both the tongue and heel and the Jumpman branding. The stripes appear in a darker gray on the midsole, while the plate of carbon fiber appears in black. Perforations appear on the bottom side of the tumbled leather application.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro PS 'Gym Red' is a preschool shoe with a familiar colorway. Built with nubuck, the upper is finished in Gym Red, with black suede overlaying the forefoot. Underfoot, the contrasting midsole houses Zoom Air and a TPU shank plate, with a herringbone outsole providing traction.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro "Desert Sand" is covered in a light beige hue and features a upper, black and white tanned suede accents and a branded shield logo on the collar. The shoe also features Infrared detailing on the heel to make the Jumpman logo and 23 stamp pop.

This 2018 grade-school edition of the Air Jordan 14 ‘Last Shot’ brings back the shoe that MJ wore when he drained the title-winning shot of the 1998 NBA Finals. This is also the final Jordan sneaker that Michael would wear as a Chicago Bull, and the team’s colors are represented by the black leather and suede upper, along with contrasting pops of Varsity Red on the heel and shank plate.

The 2005 edition of the Air Jordan 14 Retro ‘Last Shot’ brought back the iconic 1999 colorway for the first time. This was the shoe worn by Michael Jordan in Game 6 of the 1998 NBA Finals, which ended with MJ scoring the series-clinching shot – his last as a Chicago Bull. True to the original, the low-top carries an all-black exterior, accented with a yellow Jumpman badge and metallic red shank plate.

The 2011 Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Last Shot' brings back the shoe that Michael wore when he sank the series-clinching bucket in Game 6 of the 1998 Finals, his final shot with the Chicago Bulls. This reissue is true to the original, featuring an all-black upper built with a blend of tumbled leather and suede. Contrasting Varsity Red appears on the shoe’s branding hits and shank plate underfoot.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro PS 'Hyper Royal' is a preschool iteration of the shoe. The shoe's upper is built with stitched white leather, sporting perforations throughout for breathability. A Ferrari-inspired heel badge marks the quarter panel, while hits of Hyper Royal accent the look throughout. Underfoot, the midsole sports detailing that recreates the carbon-fiber shank of its full-size predecessors.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro TD 'Hyper Royal' is a toddlers' shoe. The shoe's leather upper appears in white, perforated throughout for breathability. The classic Ferrari-inspired quarter panel badge remains intact, with Hyper Royal accents emerging on the tongue, heel and midsole. Underfoot, the tooling forgoes the usual shank plate, but it includes detailing designed to recreate the look in the midfoot.

This is the 2006 reissue of the ' Candy Cane ' Air Jordan 14 Retro featuring the 1998 colorway inspired by OG Chicago Bulls. A ribbed white leather upper is used in the low-profile construction, complemented by supercar-inspired details including a Ferrari-like Jumpman badge, metallic silver aglets, and breathable mesh vents on the outsole. In the forefoot and heel, dual zoom air units provide protection and comfort.

The Jordan XIV, inspired by MJ's Ferrari 550 M, features an aerodynamic aesthetic with chiseled lines, mesh vents, metal-tipped laces, and even a Ferrari-like logo shield. The car-inspired construction is highlighted by the mixture of Light Graphite, Mid Navy, black and white colors of this 2011 version.

A 2005 release, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'White Forest Green' 2005 puts its signature color primarily on the tooling. The Air Jordan 14's signature midsole build is accented with Forest Green, a color that also makes its way to the heel and branding. The white leather upper features perforations for breathability, while a black carbon fiber midsole shank is included for support.

Paired with an Air Jordan 9 as part of the Countdown Pack, which released in the buildup to the Air Jordan 23, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Countdown Pack' features a look reminiscent of the 'Last Shot' colorway. However, the familiar black and red look emerges on a suede build with white contrast stitching rather than a tonal tumbled leather. Underfoot, a black shank plate replaces the original Varisty Red design.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro 'University Blue' emerges with a familiar University of North Carolina colorway. Featuring a black durabuck and suede upper, University Blue accents appear on the tongue, heel, branding and signature midsole design. A white carbon fiber plate offers contrast and support, with a black outsole completing the look.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro GS 'Candy Cane' 2019 is a grade-school shoe. The second retro of the colorway, the genuine and synthetic leather upper includes a tumbled finish on the quarter panel and perforations on the quarter panel and heel. Varsity Red on the tongue, heel and Phylon midsole completes the look, with Zoom Air providing cushioning.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro 'Black Toe' 2006 features a look similar to the OG 'Black Toe' colorway, but it adds perforated ribbing to the quarter panel. The shoe's signature feature is the black suede toe, while the rest of the upper appears in white leather. A metallic silver midfoot shank supports the fit, as do the dual Zoom cushioning units.

A 2005 retro, the Air Jordan 14 Retro 'White Chartreuse' is a lifestyle colorway of Michael Jordan's 14th signature shoe. Built with a white leather upper, complementary black appears on the midsole, tongue and heel. The branding, including the Jumpman badge, and midsole are all finished in vibrant chartreuse, while the Ferrari-inspired look includes a breathable vent on the midsole and dual Zoom units for cushioning.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro ‘Redwood’ shows off a sleek design that makes use of a monochromatic black suede upper, complemented by Light Graphite branding elements on the molded heel panel and a solitary hit of Redwood atop the tongue. The kicks are finished with metallic silver accents on the Jumpman badge at the lateral collar and TPU shank plate underfoot.

A girls'-exclusive colorway, the Air Jordan 14 Retro Low GG 'Phantom' features an elevated two-tone look that incorprates Phantom, Metallic Pewter and Dark Storm into its low-cut construction. Perforations throughout the leather upper are included for breathability, while the black Phylon midsole incorporates Zoom Air in the forefoot. A herringbone outsole provides traction.

The Jordan 14, originally released during the 1998-99 season, was the first signature shoe released after the second retirement of Michael Jordan. This 2005 'Chartreuse' Air Jordan 14 Retro was the first Air Jordan 14 Retro and the first to feature a complete nubuck upper. The upper Light Graphite is highlighted by vivid Chartreuse branding, while the cushioning includes a Phlon midsole and low-profile Zoom Air units.

Although it didn’t debut until Micheal Jordan’s last few games as a Chicago Bull, the Air Jordan 14 was featured in his final NBA title. The low-cut aesthetic incorporates dual Zoom units and mesh outsole vents for performance and breathability, and the subtle Air Jordan 14 Retro ‘Dark Cinder’ maintains the performance-focused look. Utilizing non-traditional basketball colors, the shoe features hits of Dark Cinder and Chutney on the midsole, tongue branding and signature Jumpman badge. Otherwise, the shoe is finished in black, white and grey.

A women's-exclusive look, the Wmns Air Jordan 14 Retro features neutral Linen hits throughout its Ferrari-inspired design. Perforations throughout the upper provide breathability, while the branding adds hits of Varsity Red. The Jumpman adds a touch of green, while Zoom Air provides cushioning underfoot.

Drawing inspiration from the color-blocked aesthetic of the ‘Black Toe’ colorway, the women’s exclusive Air Jordan 14 GS 'Fuchsia Blast' flaunts a white leather upper while its toe, tongue, and interior are dressed in black. Pops of fuchsia are seen across the silhouette, and a signature shield logo can be seen on the ankle.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro BG 'Oxidized' is a boys' and girls' colorway that forgoes the silhouette's usual perforations for tumbled leather. The Oxidized Green that gives the shoe its name appears on the branding, while the grille vent on the outsole sports more green. Underfoot, dual Zoom Air units provide cushioning.

One of five OG colorways when the Air Jordan 14 released in 1999, the Air Jordan 14 Retro BG ‘Indiglo’ recreates the look for boys' and girls' sizes. The full-grain leather and nubuck upper emerges with a mix of tumbled and smooth textures, while Vivid Green accents appear on the tongue, heel and Jumpman. A 2016 release, this shoe was the first retro to get the ‘Indiglo’ treatment.

The Air Jordan 14 Retro Low takes on a simple two-tone color scheme, featuring a white leather upper accented with Pacific Blue details on the tongue, midsole and heel, as well as the Ferrari inspired Jumpman badge on the lateral side. Subtle and unexpected pops of contrasting orange appear at the back of the midsole and the small Jumpman that adorns the top of the toe box.

Also known as the ‘Oxidized,’ this Air Jordan 14 OG was one of the original colorways of the Jordan 14, which, although it debuted during the 1998 NBA Finals, didn’t release until the following fall. The simple white leather upper sits atop a black midsole that features Dual Zoom units, with mesh vents providing breathability on the outsole. The branding, including the signature Jumpman badge, emerges in Oxidized Green.

The Air Jordan 14 OG 'Candy Cane' 1999 is an OG colorway of the last silhouette Michael Jordan wore as a Chicago Bull. The white leather upper sports perforations throughout for breathability, while Varsity Red on the branding and midsole detailing brings color to the look. Dual Zoom units and a carbon fiber shank support the fit, with a herringbone pattern underfoot for traction.

The second retro of the colorway, the Air Jordan 14 Retro TD 'Candy Cane' 2019 is a toddler-size shoe. Featuring a perforated tumbled leather upper with smooth overlays, the ankle sports the signature Ferrari-inspired Jumpman badge. Varsity Red accents throughout the Phylon foam midsole help finish the signature colorway, while a herringbone tread on the outsole provides traction.

The Air Jordan 14 OG 'Last Shot' from 1999 is one of the most iconic colorways from the Jordan franchise. Dressed in black and Varsity Red, this is the shoe that Michael wore when he drained the game-winning 20-foot jumper in the final seconds of Game 6 of 1998 NBA Finals, clinching his 6th and final ring while also acting as the swan song to his legendary career with the Chicago Bulls.

Designed by Tinker Hatfield and released in 1998, the Air Jordan 14 OG would be Michael Jordan's final signature shoe as a member of the Chicago Bulls. Rendered in white, black and Varsity Red, this inaugural colorway displays a number of vehicle-inspired information in the midsole alongside dual Zoom Air units.

Jordan Brand removed the ribbed plates that generally appear on the quarter panels to create the low-top version of the Jordan XIV's makeup. The shoe itself is influenced by the design of the Ferrari F355, featuring a Jumpman logo modified to look like the shield emblem of the car. The midsole includes a vented application that mirrors a high-performance car engine's cooling system, and the Ginger colorway was used to display a lifestyle slant while preserving performance on the court.

A preschool shoe, the Air Jordan 14 Retro PS 'Candy Cane' 2019 is the second retro of the colorway. The shoe's upper includes white tumbled leather with smooth overlays, with perforations throughout the quarter panel and heel for breathability. Varsity Red accents on the tongue, heel and throughout the Phylon midsole complete the classic look, with a shank plate underfoot providing stability.

Inspired by the Ferrari 550 M from Michael Jordan, the Air Jordan 14 was first released in 1999. Updating the classic model and paying homage to Laney High School, the Air Jordan 14 Low OG ' Laney ' features a royal Varsity and black upper dressed in a yellow hit nubuck construction. In a Ferrari-inspired appearance, the sneaker also features metallic eyelets and the classic Jumpman logo.

The Air Jordan 14 ‘Indiglo’ dropped in 1999 as one of the silhouette’s OG colorways. Inspired by Michael Jordan’s Ferrari 550 Maranello, the shoe was conceived by Tinker Hatfield to be a wearable supercar, highlighted by dual Zoom cushioning and ventilation vents on the outsole. The low-top’s sleek lines are complemented here by a predominantly black upper, accented with Indiglo branding hits.

While the silhouette represents the last shoe that Michael wore on court with the Chicago Bulls, the Air Jordan 14 Low OG ‘UNC’ recognizes the start of the athlete’s winning ways, his college alma mater. The sleek low-top, featuring lines inspired by MJ’s Ferrari, features a white leather upper with Columbia Blue accents on the midsole, tongue and heel.

The second colorway of the Air Jordan 21 Low, this model features a familiar 'Bred' look. The shoe's black suede upper is accented by hits of Varsity Red, supported underfoot by a Phylon midsole with four Independent Podular Supsension pods. The interchangeable heel allows for a choice between Zoom Air and encapsulated Air.

Inspired by the Bentley Continental GT, the Air Jordan 21 ‘Red Suede’ shows off a luxurious build in a bold, head-turning hue. This OG 2006 colorway sports a minimalist design appointed with grille-like mesh inserts and metallic silver detailing. The shoe’s innovative cushioning technology takes the form of an Independent Podular System, allowing wearers to choose between Zoom and Encapsulated Air.

The Air Jordan 21 'Varsity Red Metallic Silver' 2006 features a white leather upper inspired by Michael Jordan's Bentley Continental GT. Black mesh paneling is included for breathability, while University Red on the eyelets, heel and lining complete a Chicago Bulls look. The Phylon midsole is supported by Independent Podular Suspension technology and a carbon fiber shank plate, while the outsole sports a DNA double helix pattern.

The Air Jordan 21 'Flint Grey' launched in 2006 as one of the silhouette’s seven OG colorways. The mid-top sports a full-grain leather upper in black, accented with contrast white stitching and Flint Grey detailing around the heel and midsole. Performance benefits include a seamless inner sleeve, carbon fiber shank plate and an Independent Podular System for customizable cushioning.

Originally released in 2008 alongside an accompanying Air Jordan 2, the Air Jordan 21 Retro ‘Countdown Pack’ features a classic Chicago-inspired color scheme. The mid-top sports a premium black suede upper with contrasting pops of red on the eyelets, heel panel and outsole. Unique details include a diamond quilted lining and tonal black ‘23’ on the lateral collar.

D’Wayne Edwards looked to MJ’s 2005 Bentley Continental GT for inspiration when he designed the Air Jordan 21. That automotive sensibility is seen on the shoe’s streamlined profile, which is outfitted here in an all-suede upper in Lite Graphite. Contrasting pops of white and University Blue appear on the heel and midsole, fitted with dual grille-like vents and a carbon fiber shank plate.

The prevailing design theme that permeates the Air Jordan 21 is a feeling of luxury, a sensibility that carries on with the low-top iteration of the shoe. Here, the 21 Low borrows a page from MJ’s past with a colorway inspired by the University of North Carolina. A tumbled leather upper in white is accented with pops of University Blue on the lining, heel panel and grille-like vents on the side panel.

Drawing inspiration from the artists' favorite Jordan silhouette is the Billie Eilish x Air Jordan 15 Retro. A tan hue is on the 100% vegan build made with 20% recycled materials. Decorative stitching is on the synthetic leather upper with dual Jumpman and Billie Eilish branding on the custom insole, while the artist's Blohsh logo is on the interior tongue. It's built on a matching tan injection-molded Phylon midsole with Zoom Air cushioning in the forefoot and heel. Underneath is a durable rubber outsole which features a herringbone tread for better grip.

The Air Jordan 15 Retro 'Stealth' 2017 puts a blacked-out colorway on a silhouette inspired by the X-15 fighter jet. The full-grain leather upper features a woven crosshatch pattern, with the signature protruding tongue worked tonally into the build. Supported by a Pebax heel counter, the heel strip emerges in Varsity Red.

The Air Jordan 15 ‘Doernbecher’ is the only Jordan model from the 2018 Freestyle Collection. Donovon Dineen, the young designer, played on the influence of his favorite anime, resulting in a black suede upper embossed with a subdued dragon-scale pattern. Shimmering gold highlights on the heel and interior tongue display Donovon’s birthdate and the Japanese character for protection, respectively.

The Air Jordan 15 Retro 'Obsidian' 2017 features a dark Obsidian throughout its woven Kevlar upper, with white contrast on the heel and protruding tongue. The split color-blocking continues down onto the midsole, which, unlike the OG model, only houses Zoom Air in the heel.

The PSNY x Air Jordan 15 Retro 'Black Suede' emerges with a simple two-tone color scheme that trades the usual woven upper for a smooth suede construction. Featuring a contrasting Sail sole unit underfoot, the tip of the protruding tongue sports 'WNL'—We Need Leaders—and the rubber heel counter reads 'PSNY.'

New York City-based fashion label Public School collaborated with Jordan Brand for the PSNY x Air Jordan 15 Retro ‘Medium Olive.’ The subdued colorway features Medium Olive throughout the Kevlar aramid fiber upper. The tonal protruding tongue sports Public School’s ‘WNL’ logo (We Need Leaders), while the midsole emerges with a mix of contrasting white and complementary Medium Olive. The heel strip also has ‘PSNY’ branding as a nod to the collaboration.

The Air Jordan 15, inspired by the X-15 fighter jet, features an unconventional design, highlighted by a protruding tongue that peaks above a Kevlar woven top. This mostly black colorway from 2007 adds laser-etched designs to the white leather overlays that depict the outsoles of different Jordan models. Subtle branding on the Pebax heel counter takes the form of an integrated Jumpman logo.

This Air Jordan 15 Retro is drawn from the 2008 Countdown Pack, which also included the OG Air Jordan 8 colorway in white, black and True Red. The first Air Jordan model that would never be worn on court by His Airness, the Jordan 15 arrives in a Chicago-inspired black and red design. Unique details include a woven Kevlar aramid fiber upper and a protruding tongue inspired by MJ himself.

The Air Jordan 15 Retro GS 'Doernbecher' 2018 is the kids'-sized edition of a show released in partnership with Doernbecher Children's Hospital, a collaboration that enables patients to create their own Nike gear. Designed by then-11-year-old Donovon Dinneen, the shoe takes a cue from his favorite anime show. It features a plush black suede upper with an embossed dragon-scale pattern, with gold hints that include personal details, including Donovon’s birthday and the Japanese character for peace.

In 2000, three colorways, including this white and Columbia Blue variant, formally revealed the Air Jordan 15. The design is inspired by the X-15 fighter jet and features an aerodynamic shape and blended leather and kevlar mesh materials on top of a Zoom Air cushioned sole.

The first Air Jordan silhouette to release following Michael Jordan’s second retirement, the Air Jordan 15 OG was one of its launch colorways. The X-15 fighter jet-inspired look emerges with Nike’s signature Obsidian throughout its upper, which features Kevlar aramid fiber. White on the toe and heel, as well as the protruding collar, provides contrast, with Zoom Air providing cushioning underfoot.

The Air Jordan 15 Retro SE ‘Bragging Rights’ dropped in 2008 as a two-piece pack inspired by the 1982 NCAA championship game, which saw a young Michael Jordan scoring the winning shot. This pair gives the nod to MJ’s UNC alma mater, featuring a white woven leather upper with University Blue accents and the Tar Heels’ signature argyle print at the tongue and midsole.

The Air Jordan 15 OG ‘Stealth’ launched in 1999, continuing the Jordan franchise even as Michael stepped away from the game for a second time. Designed by Tinker Hatfield, the mid-top features a polarizing look, dominated by woven Kevlar construction in black. A protruding tongue recalls MJ’s own on-court tic, while the shoe itself is inspired by the X-15 fighter jet.

The Air Jordan 15 Low OG from 2000 showcases a design that keeps many of the details from its full-height counterpart. They include woven Kevlar fiber, now relegated to the black collar, as well as the signature protruding tongue. The black colorway amplifies the shoe’s stealthy design, inspired by the X-15 fighter jet, while pops of metallic silver add a bit of polish to the Jumpman logo and midsole.

One of the OG colorways of the silhouette, the Air Jordan 15 OG 'Flint Grey' features a subdued palette on its aggressive design. The construction, inspired by the X-15 fighter jet, features a white leather upper complemented by a Flint Grey woven build. More Flint Grey emerges on the rubber heel, sole and tongue, while the shoe also features a concealed lacing system and a Zoom Air insole.

The Air Jordan 9 Retro 'Chile Red' draws inspiration from 2012's 'Motorboat Jones' colorway. Vibrant red features throughout, from the textile utilized on the upper to the speed lacing system. The theme continues through to the tonal patent leather on the mudguard, collar and heel. Black accents arrive on the tongue tag, molded eyelets and pull loop at the heel. A glossy red polyurethane midsole and black rubber outsole complete the iteration. The Jordan 9 'Chile Red' will drop on May 7, 2022.

Made for older kids with a fiery colorway is the Air Jordan 9 Retro GS 'Chile Red.' The crimson textile upper is secured with speed lacing with decorative stitching and overlaid with tonal patent leather throughout the collar, mudguard, and heel with an embroidered 23 and a Jumpman logo superimposed on a globe. It's built on a color-matched foam midsole with a durable black rubber outsole.

The Air Jordan 9 Retro ‘Dark Charcoal University Gold’ brings a neutral look to the classic silhouette.
